<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-167-035 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 613 397</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC World  May 1991 v9 n5 p93(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mice on the move: Microsoft's BallPoint Mouse and Logitech'sTrackMan Portable aim to assist the traveling Windows user.andO;(portable pointing devices) (Hardware Review) (Preview)(evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lusty, Susan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microsoft Corp's $175 BallPoint Mouse and the Logitech Inc's $149TrackMan Portable are trackballs that attach to the side of anyportable computer and also do double duty as desktop mice.andO;BallPoint comes equipped with two buttons on either side that canbe set for hand preference through software.andP;  A bundled 20-inchcable and and 400-dot-per-inch (dpi) default resolution isstandard.andP;  These can be adjusted through software in smallincrements from 14 to 1400 dpi.andP;  Ballpoint plugs into 9-pin andPS/2 mouse ports.andP;  TrackMan comes equipped with secondary buttonson the front and the main button on the side, which can be used toswitch hand preference.andP;  A 24-inch cord and resolution defaults to200 dpi, but it can be adjusted through the software to between 50and 15,000 dpi.andP;  TrackMan supports 9-pin and 25-pin serial portsand the PS/2 port interface.andP;  Both mice are compatible with theMicrosoft Mouse, are easy to install and support Windows 3.0.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Products)Logitech Inc. (Products).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   Microsoft Ballpoint Mouse (Trackball device)Logitech TrackMan Portable (Trackball device).andO;Topic:     TrackballsEvaluationMicePortable Computers.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographtable.andO;Caption:   Product information. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>